1
00:00:20,040 --> 00:00:22,870
Now, I know this is a car show,

2
00:00:22,920 --> 00:00:25,950
but please bear with us, because
I want to talk about this.

3
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:30,150
It's one of those watches that
are worn by people who play golf

4
00:00:30,200 --> 00:00:31,550
and do business.

5
00:00:31,600 --> 00:00:36,430
And they're always banging on about
these pins, that you can see here.

6
00:00:36,480 --> 00:00:39,630
Yeah. They say that if
they pull those pins out,

7
00:00:39,680 --> 00:00:42,150
the watch will send
their precise position

8
00:00:42,200 --> 00:00:45,470
to a team of professionals,
who will come and rescue them.

9
00:00:45,520 --> 00:00:47,670
So, if they're out
climbing a mountain,

10
00:00:47,720 --> 00:00:49,030
or rowing across an ocean...

11
00:00:49,080 --> 00:00:51,990
Which they aren't, because they're
playing golf and doing business.

12
00:00:52,040 --> 00:00:54,750
No, but if they were doing those
things and something went wrong,

13
00:00:54,800 --> 00:00:56,990
then, thanks to their
watch, they'd be OK.

14
00:00:57,040 --> 00:00:58,390
Ah, but would they?

15
00:00:58,440 --> 00:01:01,470
To find out, the producers
decided that one of us

16
00:01:01,520 --> 00:01:05,270
should be dumped somewhere with minimal
kit, with virtually no food,

17
00:01:05,320 --> 00:01:07,630
somewhere very, very remote,

18
00:01:07,680 --> 00:01:09,950
to see if the system works.

19
00:01:46,080 --> 00:01:47,420
Well...

20
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:51,310
.. that's it.

21
00:01:51,360 --> 00:01:54,040
I am now marooned here...

22
00:01:55,560 --> 00:01:58,030
.. wherever the hell "here" is.

23
00:02:00,720 --> 00:02:02,390
Bloody hell...

24
00:02:05,280 --> 00:02:09,760
My only hope now is my watch, so...

25
00:02:11,200 --> 00:02:12,800
.. it's time.

26
00:02:13,600 --> 00:02:15,270
I undo this...

27
00:02:16,760 --> 00:02:18,300
.. there...

28
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:21,500
.. and then, pull that bit out...

29
00:02:22,440 --> 00:02:24,510
.. and that's it, done.

30
00:02:27,080 --> 00:02:30,430
Pulling those pins activates
a distress signal

31
00:02:30,480 --> 00:02:34,350
that's picked up by a LEOSAR
low Earth polar orbit satellite,

32
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:37,110
which then forwards
my exact coordinates

33
00:02:37,160 --> 00:02:39,070
to a central command centre.

34
00:02:39,120 --> 00:02:40,870
The team here then scramble

35
00:02:40,920 --> 00:02:43,990
the nearest highly-trained
search and rescue unit,

36
00:02:44,040 --> 00:02:47,000
who arrive at my location
within hours.

37
00:02:50,240 --> 00:02:51,510
Sadly, however,

38
00:02:51,560 --> 00:02:55,350
today, the scramble command
has not been sent

39
00:02:55,400 --> 00:02:58,400
to a highly-trained search
and rescue unit.

40
00:03:09,040 --> 00:03:11,830
- .. Running on petrol.
- It's a brilliant idea.

41
00:03:11,880 --> 00:03:14,190
- I'm not sure the Ferrari does that.
- DEVICE BEEPS

42
00:03:14,240 --> 00:03:16,870
I think it does, but I think they're
just being honest about it,

43
00:03:16,920 --> 00:03:18,390
because they're recognising that

44
00:03:18,440 --> 00:03:20,310
it's a means of improving
the efficiency...

45
00:03:20,360 --> 00:03:22,710
Is that your bag ringing?

46
00:03:22,760 --> 00:03:25,990
Oh, I think this is the signal
from our esteemed colleague,

47
00:03:26,040 --> 00:03:29,070
- Richard Hammond.
- Is it? Where is he?
- Wait a minute.

48
00:03:29,120 --> 00:03:31,710
He would appear to be in... Africa.

49
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:34,160
- Is it?
- Let's have a look.

50
00:03:34,480 --> 00:03:39,390
No, I'll think you'll
find that is... Canada.

51
00:03:39,440 --> 00:03:42,070
Specifically, the Rockies.

52
00:03:42,120 --> 00:03:43,630
Crikey. Um...

53
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:45,470
Actually, that is quite serious.

54
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:48,550
We really do need to get
on with this, James, so...

55
00:03:48,600 --> 00:03:49,910
Excuse me?

56
00:03:49,960 --> 00:03:52,360
Could we see the pudding menu?

57
00:03:53,560 --> 00:03:54,960
Right...

58
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:59,400
That bit suspends off this bit...

59
00:04:02,920 --> 00:04:05,960
- That watch transmits for 24 hours...
- WATCH BEEPS

60
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:10,070
.. and then, that's it.

61
00:04:12,680 --> 00:04:15,110
Right, so, this is the mountain,

62
00:04:15,160 --> 00:04:17,190
there's my tent.

63
00:04:17,240 --> 00:04:20,150
Mountain, trees, hills,
this is all we are.

64
00:04:20,200 --> 00:04:22,470
There's a cameraman,
a sound recordist

65
00:04:22,520 --> 00:04:25,830
and a bloke from the office --
and he's just a media luvvie.

66
00:04:25,880 --> 00:04:30,590
I know you think there's a five-star
hotel just down there,

67
00:04:30,640 --> 00:04:32,470
but there's not.

68
00:04:32,520 --> 00:04:35,820
Nothing else. There's no
survival experts here.

69
00:04:36,320 --> 00:04:38,550
Fact of the matter is,
I'm completely stuck

70
00:04:38,600 --> 00:04:41,540
until Yogi the Bore
and Boo-Boo get here.

71
00:04:43,720 --> 00:04:45,550
Knowing we were his only hope,

72
00:04:45,600 --> 00:04:48,390
we had some important
decisions to make.

73
00:04:48,440 --> 00:04:52,070
"Raunchy apple fritters" sounds quite
interesting. Pancake with cheese...

74
00:04:52,120 --> 00:04:54,110
James? James, James, James...

75
00:04:54,160 --> 00:04:55,590
You know in the colonies --

76
00:04:55,640 --> 00:04:58,390
Australia, South Africa,
America, Canada and so on?

77
00:04:58,440 --> 00:05:01,550
- Everybody loves pick-up trucks, yes?
- Yes.

78
00:05:01,600 --> 00:05:05,630
Well, why don't we get a pick-up
truck to go and rescue Hammond in?

79
00:05:05,680 --> 00:05:08,110
Because pick-up trucks generally
only have two seats

80
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:10,510
and there would be three of
us, when we've rescued him.

81
00:05:10,560 --> 00:05:13,430
Well, we get two pick-up trucks
-- one for you, one for me.

82
00:05:13,480 --> 00:05:16,510
It would A, increase our
chances of finding him,

83
00:05:16,560 --> 00:05:19,310
and B, there'd be a seat
to get him back in.

84
00:05:19,360 --> 00:05:22,750
- But...
- In Thunderbirds...

85
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:26,550
Inevitably, One and Two kind of
went first, didn't they? Always?

86
00:05:26,600 --> 00:05:27,750
Yeah.

87
00:05:27,800 --> 00:05:31,390
Alan and... No, not Alan.
Who drove Thunderbird One?

88
00:05:31,440 --> 00:05:32,950
- Scott.
- Virgil.

89
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:35,270
- No, Virgil was Two.
- Was he Two?

90
00:05:35,320 --> 00:05:37,670
Scott was One,

91
00:05:37,720 --> 00:05:40,670
Virgil was Two, Alan was
Three, Gordon was Four...

92
00:05:40,720 --> 00:05:42,060
Gordon!

93
00:05:43,080 --> 00:05:46,590
In Canada, the temperature
was a bitter minus ten,

94
00:05:46,640 --> 00:05:49,180
so I urgently needed some warmth.

95
00:05:56,760 --> 00:06:00,360
What would have been wrong
with giving me a lighter?

96
00:06:01,120 --> 00:06:04,120
Can't get my fire lit. Cold beans.

97
00:06:05,560 --> 00:06:08,230
They're a bit frozen in the middle.

98
00:06:13,080 --> 00:06:15,710
'Having finished our lunch...'

99
00:06:15,760 --> 00:06:17,630
I'm not sure about the red, you know?

100
00:06:17,680 --> 00:06:20,780
'We went to book some
flights to Vancouver.'

101
00:06:21,680 --> 00:06:24,710
OK, you've actually just missed
the last flight out today.

102
00:06:24,760 --> 00:06:26,750
- Have we?
- Yeah.
- Oh, what a rotten bit of luck.

103
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:28,190
Shouldn't we get another drink?

104
00:06:28,240 --> 00:06:31,470
There's a Delta one that leads
at ten o'clock tomorrow morning.

105
00:06:31,520 --> 00:06:34,350
I don't like Delta's seat upholstery.

106
00:06:34,400 --> 00:06:36,510
Would you go from Manchester?

107
00:06:36,560 --> 00:06:39,510
Manchester? No, you
know, this is the BBC.

108
00:06:39,560 --> 00:06:41,630
I think it would be idiotic
to go to Manchester.

109
00:06:41,680 --> 00:06:45,190
- I mean, that would be just stupid.
- There's Lufthansa...

110
00:06:45,240 --> 00:06:47,150
Er, stewardesses wear trousers.

111
00:06:47,200 --> 00:06:50,230
- There's one from Gatwick,
which goes via Calgary...
- Gatwick?

112
00:06:50,280 --> 00:06:52,870
- He doesn't like Gatwick.
- I hate Gatwick.

113
00:06:52,920 --> 00:06:54,600
WOLF HOWLS

114
00:07:01,320 --> 00:07:03,390
Out there, somewhere...

115
00:07:04,600 --> 00:07:07,280
.. there are bears...

116
00:07:09,080 --> 00:07:11,720
.. as many as 180,000 black bears.

117
00:07:13,160 --> 00:07:16,960
I can't remember what it was
-- about 15,000 grizzlies?

118
00:07:22,560 --> 00:07:23,960
Freezing.

119
00:07:28,920 --> 00:07:32,790
In the morning, I was cold and
exhausted from lack of sleep --

120
00:07:32,840 --> 00:07:35,440
but most of all, I was anxious.

121
00:07:39,680 --> 00:07:42,150
- Any minute now.
- WATCH BEEPS

122
00:07:42,560 --> 00:07:44,100
Any minute.

123
00:07:46,080 --> 00:07:48,420
I mean, they've had 24 hours.

124
00:07:51,200 --> 00:07:53,000
I mean, 24 hours?

125
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:57,640
You can get anywhere in the
world in 24 hours, surely?

126
00:08:02,680 --> 00:08:04,710
Where the hell are they?

127
00:08:04,760 --> 00:08:06,500
JET ENGINES ROAR

128
00:08:14,080 --> 00:08:16,550
- I can't remember...
- James?

129
00:08:17,560 --> 00:08:21,350
- We've stopped beeping.
- Well, yeah. It would.
- Why would it?

130
00:08:21,400 --> 00:08:25,270
Cos the watch thing only transmits
the distress signal for 24 hours.

131
00:08:25,320 --> 00:08:27,520
Then the battery runs out.

132
00:08:27,840 --> 00:08:29,630
- Seriously?
- Well, yeah. It's only...

133
00:08:29,680 --> 00:08:32,710
- Well, did you make a note of where he was?
- No, I didn't.

134
00:08:32,760 --> 00:08:34,760
You've got the thing.

135
00:08:35,800 --> 00:08:39,030
Well, I remember he was...
He was on something called...

136
00:08:39,080 --> 00:08:43,550
I think it was "Wolf Mountain"
and you go up "Bear Pass".

137
00:08:43,600 --> 00:08:45,510
Sounds GRIZZLY.

138
00:08:45,560 --> 00:08:46,830
LAUGHTER

139
00:08:46,880 --> 00:08:48,230
That was a good joke.

140
00:08:48,280 --> 00:08:51,560
Do you know, actually, the biggest
problem is not bears and wolves...

141
00:08:52,640 --> 00:08:55,470
- Cougars. Loads of cougars.
- Well, that's all right, then.

142
00:08:55,520 --> 00:08:57,470
No, not that sort of cougar.

143
00:08:57,520 --> 00:08:59,590
[JEREMY GROWLS] That sort of cougar.

144
00:08:59,640 --> 00:09:02,240
Oh, you mean like a big cat thing?

145
00:09:04,400 --> 00:09:06,510
As I couldn't move from the spot

146
00:09:06,560 --> 00:09:09,510
where the watch had transmitted
the distress signal,

147
00:09:09,560 --> 00:09:13,480
I was hard at work trying to make
my life here more comfortable.

148
00:09:20,080 --> 00:09:21,910
I want somewhere to sit.

149
00:09:21,960 --> 00:09:25,560
I can't sit on the snow,
so I'm building a shelter.

150
00:09:34,440 --> 00:09:36,310
Spark, you [BLEEP!]

151
00:09:37,600 --> 00:09:39,590
There we go.

152
00:09:39,640 --> 00:09:41,240
We have fire.

153
00:09:41,920 --> 00:09:44,190
And with my supplies dwindling,

154
00:09:44,240 --> 00:09:46,840
I also needed to think about food.

155
00:09:48,280 --> 00:09:50,150
Animals for food...

156
00:09:51,720 --> 00:09:53,830
.. guinea pigs.

157
00:09:53,880 --> 00:09:56,390
All animals can be a
source of nourishment.

158
00:09:56,440 --> 00:10:00,560
A few, including worms and insects,
can be collected with little skill.

159
00:10:10,880 --> 00:10:13,590
I'm bored, I'm cold, I'm unhappy,

160
00:10:13,640 --> 00:10:15,950
I'm hungry, I'm scared...

161
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:17,910
Agh!

162
00:10:17,960 --> 00:10:21,310
And I don't want to be wearing
a hat, just for a minute!

163
00:10:21,360 --> 00:10:22,500
Ah!

164
00:10:24,240 --> 00:10:27,990
To alleviate the boredom
and stave off the cold,

165
00:10:28,040 --> 00:10:31,360
I tried to make some SAS-style
pine needle tea.

166
00:10:34,480 --> 00:10:36,510
Agh!

167
00:10:36,560 --> 00:10:39,030
Ow, ow!

168
00:10:39,080 --> 00:10:40,870
Ow!

169
00:10:40,920 --> 00:10:43,260
Where are they?! Just where?

170
00:10:48,880 --> 00:10:53,510
'Unfortunately, we were a little
bit delayed at Vancouver airport.'

171
00:10:53,560 --> 00:10:55,630
Yes, of course.

172
00:10:55,680 --> 00:10:58,590
'But eventually, we made
it to the car park,

173
00:10:58,640 --> 00:11:02,830
'where our pick-up truck rescue
vehicles were waiting.'

174
00:11:02,880 --> 00:11:05,440
MUSIC: The Launch by Boston

175
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:22,710
- James?
- Yeah?

176
00:11:22,760 --> 00:11:25,550
That's not a light, that's
a collapsed sun, isn't it?

177
00:11:25,600 --> 00:11:27,310
Never mind that, look --

178
00:11:27,360 --> 00:11:30,710
mine actually comes up to my nipples.

179
00:11:30,760 --> 00:11:33,950
I didn't realise it was... Do you
know what the other thing is?

180
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:37,670
If I actually find Richard Hammond,
I'm not going to see him, and I?

181
00:11:37,720 --> 00:11:39,230
I'll just run straight over him.

182
00:11:39,280 --> 00:11:41,230
Have you noticed something
else about mine?

183
00:11:41,280 --> 00:11:42,950
This entire vehicle...

184
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:46,230
is a transportation device
for its own spare wheel, look!

185
00:11:46,280 --> 00:11:47,830
That's all the back is for!

186
00:11:47,880 --> 00:11:51,430
- That's really stupid.
Look at the size of it!
- Look at it!

187
00:11:51,480 --> 00:11:53,470
Anyway, we've got
everything we need here.

188
00:11:53,520 --> 00:11:55,870
I've got a big, warm coat,
I've got a massive car,

189
00:11:55,920 --> 00:11:58,510
a rough idea of where
Richard Hammond is...

190
00:11:58,560 --> 00:12:00,270
Yeah, so let's go...

191
00:12:00,320 --> 00:12:03,630
into Vancouver, get a hotel,
good night's rest,

192
00:12:03,680 --> 00:12:05,820
get rid of this jet lag.

193
00:12:06,440 --> 00:12:08,280
ENGINE REVS

194
00:12:11,760 --> 00:12:14,230
It's not funny. I don't know...

195
00:12:14,760 --> 00:12:17,870
They've got to get here tomorrow...

196
00:12:17,920 --> 00:12:19,720
morning -- early.

197
00:12:26,800 --> 00:12:29,560
WOLF HOWLS

198
00:12:37,200 --> 00:12:39,470
Now, my guest tonight was
Jordan Belfort's wife

199
00:12:39,520 --> 00:12:40,910
in The Wolf Of Wall Street,

200
00:12:40,960 --> 00:12:43,470
one of my favourite films
of the modern age.

201
00:12:43,520 --> 00:12:47,790
She's now in a new film and she's
brought along her co-star,

202
00:12:47,840 --> 00:12:49,870
so please welcome Margot Robbie

203
00:12:49,920 --> 00:12:52,510
and a man called Will Smith!

204
00:12:52,560 --> 00:12:55,070
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE

205
00:12:55,120 --> 00:12:56,990
Oh, heavens above!

206
00:12:59,120 --> 00:13:00,990
Look what we've got for you!

207
00:13:01,040 --> 00:13:03,030
Yeah, we got you as well.

208
00:13:03,080 --> 00:13:05,670
Good to see you, good to see you.

209
00:13:05,720 --> 00:13:08,230
Good to see you both.
I'll go round here.

210
00:13:08,280 --> 00:13:11,020
- Thanks for having us.
- And relax.

211
00:13:14,280 --> 00:13:15,820
Have a seat.

212
00:13:16,680 --> 00:13:18,270
Have a seat.

213
00:13:18,320 --> 00:13:21,950
- This is fantastic!
- Isn't this fantastic?
- This is great.

214
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:25,870
I was almost going to begin by
apologising for the trailers.

215
00:13:25,920 --> 00:13:29,750
- The trailers? Oh, those trailers, yeah.
- They're really nice.

216
00:13:29,800 --> 00:13:34,150
- Will set his bar very high
with trailers though, so...
- Really?

217
00:13:34,200 --> 00:13:35,790
Yeah, his trailer is pimp.

218
00:13:35,840 --> 00:13:38,150
Yeah, I'm very serious
about the trailer.

219
00:13:38,200 --> 00:13:39,710
The trailer, it has to be...

220
00:13:39,760 --> 00:13:43,350
You've got to hook it up, you've
got to have a stereo system...

221
00:13:43,400 --> 00:13:45,590
Yours had mirrors on the roof.

222
00:13:45,640 --> 00:13:47,350
LAUGHTER

223
00:13:47,400 --> 00:13:48,830
MOUTHS: No, it didn't.

224
00:13:48,880 --> 00:13:52,230
I'm not insinuating anything,
I'm just saying...

225
00:13:52,280 --> 00:13:54,870
That's going to get in trouble.

226
00:13:54,920 --> 00:13:56,590
That's going to get into trouble.

227
00:13:56,640 --> 00:13:59,580
Already in trouble,
where my mind's gone.

228
00:14:00,600 --> 00:14:03,790
- Really, not that long ago,
you were in Neighbours.
- Yeah.

229
00:14:03,840 --> 00:14:07,030
What interests me about Neighbours,
which is an Aussie TV show...

230
00:14:07,080 --> 00:14:09,910
- I know what Neighbours is, man!
- Don't pretend you know!

231
00:14:09,960 --> 00:14:11,230
I know what Neighbours is...

232
00:14:11,280 --> 00:14:14,230
Two days ago, they asked him
what show I did in Australia --

233
00:14:14,280 --> 00:14:16,750
a very popular show -- and you
said it started with "C"...

234
00:14:16,800 --> 00:14:19,630
- I couldn't remember the name...
- There's no "C" in it.

235
00:14:19,680 --> 00:14:22,230
I just can't see Will Smith
finishing a day at work going,

236
00:14:22,280 --> 00:14:24,550
"Do you know, I think
I'll watch Neighbours."

237
00:14:24,600 --> 00:14:28,310
- "6.30, my show's on!"
- Russell Crowe started in that, didn't he?

238
00:14:28,360 --> 00:14:31,030
- Guy Pearce was another
one, Kylie's another one...
- Yeah, yeah.

239
00:14:31,080 --> 00:14:33,790
And I always wondered, do
you know Coronation Street?

240
00:14:33,840 --> 00:14:36,950
- Because that's produced literally...
- Yeah, I know all those shows, man!

241
00:14:37,000 --> 00:14:40,760
- You don't. And...
- I've got the DVDs and everything!

242
00:14:42,360 --> 00:14:46,150
- It's just unbelievable.
- I have all this, the... the...

243
00:14:46,200 --> 00:14:48,950
Coronation Street and
Neighbours and all those.

244
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:51,310
EastEnders, yeah.

245
00:14:51,360 --> 00:14:55,110
- Now, you're over here,
obviously, to promote a film.
