00:26:25,760 --> 00:26:28,510
LAUGHTER

480
00:26:28,560 --> 00:26:31,710
- .. 7...
- Oh!
- AUDIENCE GASPS

481
00:26:31,760 --> 00:26:34,030
She'd better not, she'd better not...

482
00:26:34,080 --> 00:26:37,320
- .. 1!
- Oh!
- CHEERING AND APPLAUSE

483
00:26:38,920 --> 00:26:40,920
I'm not making it up!

484
00:26:43,440 --> 00:26:44,910
I'm sorry!

485
00:26:50,680 --> 00:26:52,680
[BLEEP!]

486
00:27:00,720 --> 00:27:02,660
This was a bad idea.

487
00:27:03,960 --> 00:27:05,310
It's like the Academy Awards,

488
00:27:05,360 --> 00:27:08,560
where you've got to clap
for the other person.

489
00:27:15,280 --> 00:27:18,030
- I don't know what to say now.
- I actually can't believe that.

490
00:27:18,080 --> 00:27:20,230
- Both of you have done amazing times.
- Oh, my God!

491
00:27:20,280 --> 00:27:21,790
There was a tenth in it,

492
00:27:21,840 --> 00:27:24,230
neither of you have got anything
to be ashamed about.

493
00:27:24,280 --> 00:27:26,670
Oh, no -- one of us has something
to be ashamed about!

494
00:27:26,720 --> 00:27:28,030
LAUGHTER

495
00:27:28,080 --> 00:27:30,750
- I was trying to end on a really high note...
- No, no...

496
00:27:30,800 --> 00:27:33,070
.. coming up with some nice things...

497
00:27:33,120 --> 00:27:34,920
But you're right.

498
00:27:36,440 --> 00:27:38,630
Ladies and gentlemen, I
think you'll all agree,

499
00:27:38,680 --> 00:27:41,510
this has been an absolute joy.
Will Smith and Margot Robbie!

500
00:27:41,560 --> 00:27:43,560
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE

501
00:27:54,200 --> 00:27:58,910
Now, last year, McLaren
gave us the astonishing P1

502
00:27:58,960 --> 00:28:02,830
and Porsche gave us the
equally fantastic 918,

503
00:28:02,880 --> 00:28:07,830
but we've always known that there
is another hybrid supercar coming.

504
00:28:07,880 --> 00:28:10,310
Well, it's not coming any more.

505
00:28:10,360 --> 00:28:12,910
It's here, it's the one you've
all been waiting for

506
00:28:12,960 --> 00:28:14,990
and I have been driving it.

507
00:28:15,040 --> 00:28:18,000
The Ferrari "The Ferrari"!

508
00:28:27,840 --> 00:28:29,950
McLaren and Porsche may believe

509
00:28:30,000 --> 00:28:34,080
they've created good-looking
cars in the P1 and the 918...

510
00:28:38,400 --> 00:28:42,550
.. but I think they need to get
their pencil cases out again,

511
00:28:42,600 --> 00:28:46,560
because this is what a
supercar should look like.

512
00:29:01,920 --> 00:29:05,230
And this is what a supercar
should sound like.

513
00:29:05,280 --> 00:29:09,080
ENGINE THRUMS AND REVS

514
00:29:14,560 --> 00:29:18,430
No miserable V8s or puny
little turbochargers --

515
00:29:18,480 --> 00:29:21,120
that is Ferrari's greatest hit.

516
00:29:23,960 --> 00:29:28,670
The sound of 12 cylinders
properly arranged in a V.

517
00:29:28,720 --> 00:29:30,520
Molto grazie!

518
00:29:37,800 --> 00:29:39,590
And then, there's the price --

519
00:29:39,640 --> 00:29:43,140
LaFerrari has the other
two licked there, as well.

520
00:29:44,600 --> 00:29:48,510
The Porsche 918 -- £646,000.

521
00:29:48,560 --> 00:29:52,670
The McLaren P1 -- £866,000.

522
00:29:52,720 --> 00:29:54,460
The LaFerrari...

523
00:29:55,800 --> 00:29:57,550
£1,000,000!

524
00:29:57,600 --> 00:30:00,540
That's a proper price
-- no mucking about!

525
00:30:02,040 --> 00:30:04,070
'And there's more.'

526
00:30:04,120 --> 00:30:06,630
Pinky and Perky have
been at great pains

527
00:30:06,680 --> 00:30:10,520
to explain just how clever the
McLaren and the Porsche are.

528
00:30:12,200 --> 00:30:14,920
Well, this is also very clever.

529
00:30:18,960 --> 00:30:24,430
'It's built from not one, but four
different types of carbon fibre

530
00:30:24,480 --> 00:30:27,070
'to keep it as light as possible.

531
00:30:27,120 --> 00:30:30,200
'In fact, it's lighter than
the Porsche or the McLaren.

532
00:30:31,760 --> 00:30:33,470
'The driver's seat is fixed

533
00:30:33,520 --> 00:30:36,590
'and instead it's the wheel
and pedals that move.

534
00:30:36,640 --> 00:30:39,310
'This means you don't
need a seat mechanism,

535
00:30:39,360 --> 00:30:42,790
'which means the driver can sit
lower, the roof can be lower

536
00:30:42,840 --> 00:30:45,780
'and that drops the
centre of gravity...

537
00:30:47,600 --> 00:30:50,470
'.. to the benefit of cornering.

538
00:30:50,520 --> 00:30:52,860
'Then we come to the engine.'

539
00:30:55,320 --> 00:30:59,630
Like the McLaren and the Porsche,
LaFerrari is a hybrid.

540
00:30:59,680 --> 00:31:03,950
It has a petrol engine AND an electric
motor to drive the wheels.

541
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:05,630
But, whereas the other two

542
00:31:05,680 --> 00:31:09,270
can be driven on electric power
alone like a Toyota Prius,

543
00:31:09,320 --> 00:31:11,070
the Ferrari can't because,

544
00:31:11,120 --> 00:31:15,040
Ferrari say, "We are not
interested in electric cars."

545
00:31:17,040 --> 00:31:20,390
'Instead, the battery and
electric motor combination

546
00:31:20,440 --> 00:31:25,030
'works a bit like the kinetic energy
recovery system in an F1 car.

547
00:31:25,080 --> 00:31:26,430
'In very simple terms,

548
00:31:26,480 --> 00:31:28,710
'it captures energy that's
normally wasted --

549
00:31:28,760 --> 00:31:30,270
'during braking, for example -'

550
00:31:30,320 --> 00:31:32,990
'and keeps it for when you need it.'

551
00:31:41,960 --> 00:31:43,950
The electric motor,
the petrol engine --

552
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:47,030
they're all working together
all of the time.

553
00:31:47,080 --> 00:31:49,280
You cannot separate them.

554
00:31:50,640 --> 00:31:54,840
This is simply a 950
horsepower supercar.

555
00:31:58,480 --> 00:32:01,590
'But, despite the racing technology,

556
00:32:01,640 --> 00:32:05,640
'you don't find yourself in a world
of austere track car misery.'

557
00:32:08,680 --> 00:32:11,910
You've got the sat-nav,
the air conditioning.

558
00:32:11,960 --> 00:32:14,550
It's perfectly comfortable.

559
00:32:14,600 --> 00:32:17,160
Actually, it's very civilised.

560
00:32:20,960 --> 00:32:24,430
'However, this is also
supposed to be the fastest

561
00:32:24,480 --> 00:32:29,150
'and most exciting road
car Ferrari has ever made.

562
00:32:29,200 --> 00:32:32,800
'And to find out how exciting,
we must come here...

563
00:32:34,160 --> 00:32:36,700
'.. Ferrari's Fiorano test track.

564
00:32:38,280 --> 00:32:41,030
'To prancing horse fans,
this is the sacred tarmac

565
00:32:41,080 --> 00:32:45,400
'where the company's greatest
F1 cars were born.

566
00:32:46,880 --> 00:32:51,710
'But, when I rolled up, sacred wasn't
the word that came to mind.'

567
00:32:51,760 --> 00:32:54,560
THUNDER RUMBLES

568
00:32:57,600 --> 00:32:59,550
Oh, cock!

569
00:32:59,600 --> 00:33:03,630
'After two hours of dithering
on the start line...'

570
00:33:03,680 --> 00:33:07,080
- WHIRRING
- Pedals -- a little bit further away.

571
00:33:07,800 --> 00:33:10,590
No, that's too far away. Hang on.

572
00:33:10,640 --> 00:33:14,280
'.. the track was finally dry
enough for me to have a go.'

573
00:33:16,640 --> 00:33:19,560
Red, red, red...

574
00:33:30,120 --> 00:33:32,240
God's holy trousers!

575
00:33:41,120 --> 00:33:43,990
Strewth, I'm already
at the first bend.

576
00:33:44,880 --> 00:33:46,620
Lots of brakes.

577
00:33:49,760 --> 00:33:54,200
That, ladies and gentlemen,
is 950 horsepower for you.

578
00:33:55,760 --> 00:33:56,990
And while we're at it,

579
00:33:57,040 --> 00:34:01,670
950 horsepower is a slam dunk
Top Trump over the other two.

580
00:34:01,720 --> 00:34:05,680
And so is the top speed -- 218mph.

581
00:34:08,120 --> 00:34:11,430
'But it's not just the amount of
horsepower that's impressive --

582
00:34:11,480 --> 00:34:14,030
'it's the way it's served up.'

583
00:34:14,080 --> 00:34:17,590
Even if you're a bit
clumsy or a bit timid,

584
00:34:17,640 --> 00:34:21,590
as I am being on this one, you've
still got that enormous grunt.

585
00:34:21,640 --> 00:34:24,440
It just hits you like
a runaway train.

586
00:34:25,960 --> 00:34:30,470
That's the KERS system working.
That's exactly what it's for.

587
00:34:30,520 --> 00:34:34,310
'On top of that, Ferrari has
remembered that not everyone

588
00:34:34,360 --> 00:34:38,080
'who'll drive this car will be
called Sebastian or Vettel.'

589
00:34:42,800 --> 00:34:46,470
Because LaFerrari will go quite
a lot faster than you can think,

590
00:34:46,520 --> 00:34:50,030
Ferrari do quite a lot of thinking
for you. It has, for example,

591
00:34:50,080 --> 00:34:53,030
a very sophisticated
traction control system

592
00:34:53,080 --> 00:34:54,630
based on Formula 1 tech.

593
00:34:54,680 --> 00:34:57,070
And you can leave it turned on.

594
00:34:57,120 --> 00:34:59,720
Why not? It stops you crashing.

595
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:05,270
'LaFerrari also bristles
with active aerodynamics.

596
00:35:05,320 --> 00:35:06,950
'That's not new on a supercar,

597
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:12,510
'but this system is controlled
by 21 computers, which means,

598
00:35:12,560 --> 00:35:14,670
'according to the Ferrari eggheads,

599
00:35:14,720 --> 00:35:19,630
'even I should be able to take
Fiorano's notorious turn seven...

600
00:35:19,680 --> 00:35:21,220
'flat out.'

601
00:35:22,880 --> 00:35:26,030
Active aerodynamics, here we go!

602
00:35:26,080 --> 00:35:28,910
Don't bottle it, don't bottle it!

603
00:35:28,960 --> 00:35:30,440
Ho-ho-ho!

604
00:35:32,680 --> 00:35:35,600
It works! Look at that!

605
00:35:37,760 --> 00:35:40,640
The faster you go,
the better it works!

606
00:35:43,200 --> 00:35:47,630
I mean, like Jennifer's McLaren,
it is pure rear-wheel drive,

607
00:35:47,680 --> 00:35:51,780
and that is quite intimidating,
but it's not a widow maker.

608
00:35:57,680 --> 00:35:59,520
Oh, my God!

609
00:36:00,640 --> 00:36:02,800
Whoa, yes!

610
00:36:06,560 --> 00:36:08,480
Wahey! Sorry.

611
00:36:10,120 --> 00:36:12,750
Let's just slow this down a bit.

612
00:36:12,800 --> 00:36:15,190
Richard Hammond, he
says the Porsche 918,

613
00:36:15,240 --> 00:36:18,670
that's the one that takes the
hybrid supercar the furthest,

614
00:36:18,720 --> 00:36:20,630
it's the most responsible,
if you like.

615
00:36:20,680 --> 00:36:23,470
Jeremy likes the P1 because
he says it takes an idea

616
00:36:23,520 --> 00:36:26,390
that was essentially
an environmental one

617
00:36:26,440 --> 00:36:29,680
and uses it to make the
supercar more dramatic.

618
00:36:31,240 --> 00:36:35,160
'In this respect, the Ferrari
is more like the McLaren.'

619
00:36:37,160 --> 00:36:41,240
Except for two things --
LaFerrari looks better...

620
00:36:42,640 --> 00:36:44,980
.. and I reckon it IS better.

621
00:36:46,640 --> 00:36:49,440
This is the greatest
car in the world!

622
00:37:11,320 --> 00:37:17,110
Now, tonight, Jeremy and I are using
two huge American pick-up trucks

623
00:37:17,160 --> 00:37:20,190
to rescue Richard Hammond,
who's been abandoned

624
00:37:20,240 --> 00:37:22,390
- LAUGHTER
- on a freezing cold mountain top

625
00:37:22,440 --> 00:37:23,790
in the Canadian Rockies.

626
00:37:23,840 --> 00:37:27,150
We pick up the action after
we'd had a good night's rest

627
00:37:27,200 --> 00:37:29,600
in a downtown Vancouver hotel.

628
00:37:41,440 --> 00:37:46,230
'We set off before dawn, not knowing
exactly where Hammond was,

629
00:37:46,280 --> 00:37:50,510
'but we did know he was
at least 400 miles away,

630
00:37:50,560 --> 00:37:54,400
'so we had plenty of time to
get to know our vehicles.'

631
00:37:56,120 --> 00:38:01,230
I am driving a Ford
F-150 pick-up truck,

632
00:38:01,280 --> 00:38:06,190
which is by miles the
best-selling vehicle in America.

633
00:38:06,240 --> 00:38:11,110
Ford sells one of these
things every 35 seconds

634
00:38:11,160 --> 00:38:13,470
and that's only in America, remember.

635
00:38:13,520 --> 00:38:15,060
35 seconds!

636
00:38:16,360 --> 00:38:19,870
If you were to park every
F-150 that's ever been made

637
00:38:19,920 --> 00:38:23,310
since 1948 side by side
-- not end to end,

638
00:38:23,360 --> 00:38:28,550
side by side -- the line would
stretch round the Equator...

639
00:38:28,600 --> 00:38:30,080
twice!

640
00:38:32,040 --> 00:38:36,750
'The reason it sells so well
is simple -- it's cheap.'

641
00:38:36,800 --> 00:38:41,070
You can have an F-150 with an
automatic gearbox, cruise control,

642
00:38:41,120 --> 00:38:43,630
air conditioning and
a 350 horsepower...

643
00:38:43,680 --> 00:38:45,150
AMERICAN ACCENT: .. V8 motor

644
00:38:45,200 --> 00:38:48,470
for the equivalent of £20,000.

645
00:38:48,520 --> 00:38:52,760
That's what we pay in Europe
for a Vauxhall Astra diesel.

646
00:38:56,920 --> 00:39:01,040
'By comparison, my pick-up
truck is a sales disaster.'

647
00:39:02,200 --> 00:39:04,870
What I'm driving here,
viewers, the Silverado --

648
00:39:04,920 --> 00:39:09,430
the Chevrolet Silverado -- is the
second-best-selling pick-up truck.

649
00:39:09,480 --> 00:39:13,080
They only manage to shift
one of these every minute.

650
00:39:13,640 --> 00:39:16,640
I'm amazed Chevrolet
are still in business.

651
00:39:18,560 --> 00:39:25,070
'Meanwhile, very far away, my third
day on the mountain was beginning.'

652
00:39:25,120 --> 00:39:29,350
I didn't sleep last night,
I was cold all night.

653
00:39:29,400 --> 00:39:32,230
I'm going to have to
get more firewood.

654
00:39:32,280 --> 00:39:36,110
The thought of that, swinging
that axe AGAIN...

655
00:39:36,160 --> 00:39:37,790
It's probably a good diet, this.

656
00:39:37,840 --> 00:39:40,750
You'll see it on This
Morning at some point.

657
00:39:40,800 --> 00:39:44,110
"Well, what you need is to be
abandoned by two good friends.

658
00:39:44,160 --> 00:39:47,860
"Well, when I say 'good
friends', I mean 'bastards'."

659
00:39:51,360 --> 00:39:54,150
- Look!
- That's what I call a breakfast.

660
00:39:54,200 --> 00:39:57,520
- Thank you very much.
- Yeah, that's perfect.

661
00:40:01,240 --> 00:40:05,550
'After our winter-warming breakfast,
we were back on the road

662
00:40:05,600 --> 00:40:09,830
'and delving once more
into our pick-up trucks.'

663
00:40:09,880 --> 00:40:11,270
I'm going to be honest with you.

664
00:40:11,320 --> 00:40:14,310
This is no ordinary F-150.

665
00:40:14,360 --> 00:40:17,190
This is the top of the
range Raptor model,

666
00:40:17,240 --> 00:40:20,710
which has been beefed up,
supercharged and intercooled

667
00:40:20,760 --> 00:40:25,710
and then renamed VelociRaptor
by a company called Hennessey,

668
00:40:25,760 --> 00:40:27,430
makers of the Venom,

669
00:40:27,480 --> 00:40:32,160
one of the fastest road cars
the world has ever seen.

670
00:40:35,160 --> 00:40:41,110
So, the 6.2 litre V8 I have under
the bonnet produces -- ahem --

671
00:40:41,160 --> 00:40:45,070
623 horsepower.

672
00:40:45,120 --> 00:40:47,520
That's 212 more than standard.

673
00:40:48,520 --> 00:40:53,150
And that makes it quick.
Alarmingly quick!

674
00:40:53,200 --> 00:40:55,550
ENGINE ROARS

675
00:40:55,600 --> 00:40:58,470
Listen to THAT!

676
00:40:58,520 --> 00:41:00,260
It's like a jet.

677
00:41:02,640 --> 00:41:05,510
'While Jeremy was in a
supercharged rocket ship,

678
00:41:05,560 --> 00:41:08,430
'I was riding a wave
of lowdown grunt.'

679
00:41:10,520 --> 00:41:17,790
I have at my disposal a 6.6 litre
turbo-charged V8 diesel engine.

680
00:41:17,840 --> 00:41:23,710
It develops 765 pound-feet of torque.

681
00:41:23,760 --> 00:41:26,800
That's more than one of those
Supersports Bentley Continentals!

682
00:41:28,640 --> 00:41:30,670
I also have the Z71 Off-Road Package,

683
00:41:30,720 --> 00:41:34,750
which means I get a lot of underbody
strengthening, beefed-up dampers

684
00:41:34,800 --> 00:41:36,110
and it has, as standard,

685
00:41:36,160 --> 00:41:38,630
a sophisticated four-wheel
drive system.

686
00:41:38,680 --> 00:41:42,270
I think, for International Rescue,
this is like Thunderbird 2.

687
00:41:42,320 --> 00:41:45,680
It's the one that does all the
really serious, proper work.

688
00:41:50,280 --> 00:41:51,990
'With 52 hours gone

689
00:41:52,040 --> 00:41:54,750
'and International Rescue
nowhere in sight,

690
00:41:54,800 --> 00:41:59,470
'I was resorting to extreme
measures to find food.'

691
00:41:59,520 --> 00:42:01,470
This is the snare.

692
00:42:01,520 --> 00:42:05,550
It just tightens like that.

693
00:42:05,600 --> 00:42:09,190
I lay this on the rabbit
trail, which is here.

694
00:42:09,240 --> 00:42:13,150
Foot -- caught, rabbit -- dinner.

695
00:42:13,200 --> 00:42:19,000
There! Apparently, the way
you bait it is with pee.

696
00:42:21,120 --> 00:42:23,030
VELCRO UNFASTENING

697
00:42:23,080 --> 00:42:24,520
ZIP OPENS

698
00:42:28,240 --> 00:42:30,640
Another layer... Two...

699
00:42:32,920 --> 00:42:34,520
Four...

700
00:42:38,040 --> 00:42:40,240
What if a bear comes now?

701
00:42:43,080 --> 00:42:46,510
'Meanwhile, James and I, keen
to be ready for any emergency,

702
00:42:46,560 --> 00:42:50,120
'had decided to buy vital
rescue equipment.'

703
00:42:51,880 --> 00:42:56,430
- What's that bit there for?
- A can opener. A bottle opener.
- What...

704
00:42:56,480 --> 00:43:01,550
- It's a bottle opener.
- It opens beer. Yes! We want them.

705
00:43:01,600 --> 00:43:03,670
- That's worth having, isn't it?
- What is it?

706
00:43:03,720 --> 00:43:06,710
- Scrapey-scrapey, brushy-brushy.
- We don't need a brush.

707
00:43:06,760 --> 00:43:10,510
Well, OK, saw the brush off.
I can't buy just one end, can I?

708
00:43:10,560 --> 00:43:12,070
No, no, see, there's just one end.

709
00:43:12,120 --> 00:43:14,230
Yeah, but you might as
well have a brush as well.

710
00:43:14,280 --> 00:43:15,510
No, you don't need a brush.

711
00:43:15,560 --> 00:43:18,630
WOLF HOWLS

712
00:43:18,680 --> 00:43:24,790
I haven't made these exactly
like the ones in the book

713
00:43:24,840 --> 00:43:27,270
cos I once saw Ray
Mears make snowshoes

714
00:43:27,320 --> 00:43:29,660
and they were more like this.

715
00:43:43,240 --> 00:43:46,870
Ahhh! Cold!

716
00:43:46,920 --> 00:43:48,760
REALLY COLD!

717
00:43:53,640 --> 00:43:55,670
That's it -- that's where I peed.

718
00:43:55,720 --> 00:43:57,640
